âœ… 3. Smallest Number of Moves to Make Array Equal
ğŸ” You are allowed to increment/decrement array elements; you need to make all elements equal with minimum moves.

ğŸ’¡ Why Merge Sort?
Sort the array using merge sort to compute median efficiently and calculate minimum moves in O(n log n).

âœ… 4. Sort a Linked List in O(n log n)
ğŸ” Sorting a singly linked list.

ğŸ’¡ Why Merge Sort?
Merge Sort is the only comparison-based algorithm that works in O(n log n) time and can be applied to linked lists efficiently (unlike quicksort which needs random access).

âœ… 5. Finding Number of Reverse Pairs
ğŸ” Like inversions, but condition is nums[i] > 2 * nums[j].

ğŸ’¡ Why Merge Sort?
During merge, count such pairs efficiently using two pointers. Naive approach is O(nÂ²); merge sort reduces it to O(n log n).

âœ… 6. Maximum of All Minimums for Every Window Size
ğŸ” This is used in sliding window problems where you need to preprocess.

ğŸ’¡ Why Merge Sort?
Merge sort tree (a variant of segment tree) can help with range queries when pre-processing is required.

âœ… 7. External Sorting (Huge Files)
ğŸ” When data doesn't fit into RAM (e.g., log files, database sorting).

ğŸ’¡ Why Merge Sort?
Merge sort can be adapted into external sort where data is divided, sorted in chunks, and merged from disk.

âœ… 8. Multi-way Merge Problems
ğŸ” Merge k sorted arrays.

ğŸ’¡ Why Merge Sort?
Recursive merge of sorted arrays is like applying merge sort on array of arrays.

Often used with priority queues + divide-and-conquer.

âœ… 9. Sorting-based Techniques
Problems like Closest Pair of Points, Minimum Number of Platforms, Meeting Rooms, Merge Intervals, etc., benefit from sorting with merge sort especially when stability or guaranteed time complexity matters.

